            <fr:title text="Inverse">Inverse</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="source">
  
  
  <fr:link href="https://git.sr.ht/~jonsterling/agda-erct/tree/main/item/agda/erct-000W.agda" type="external">erct-000W.agda</fr:link>
</fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>An <fr:em><fr:strong>inverse</fr:strong></fr:em> to a function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A \to  B]]></fr:tex> is defined to be a <fr:link href="foreign-erct-erct-000X.xml" title="Quasi-inverse" addr="//erct/erct-000X" type="local">quasi-inverse</fr:link> equipped with an additional higher coherence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\chi  \colon  \mathsf {act}_{f}\circ  \eta  \sim  \epsilon \circ  f]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\circ  g \circ  f \sim  f]]></fr:tex> relating the (<fr:em>a priori</fr:em> incoherent) unit and the counit of the quasi-inverse. We will refer to a function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\to  B]]></fr:tex> equipped with an inverse as an <fr:em><fr:strong>invertible function</fr:strong></fr:em>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="foreign-erct-jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="//erct/jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2023</fr:year>
              <fr:month>12</fr:month>
              <fr:day>19</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>11719</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">//erct/erct-0010</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>foreign-erct-erct-0010.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Path object">Path object</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="source">
  
  
  <fr:link href="https://git.sr.ht/~jonsterling/agda-erct/tree/main/item/agda/erct-0010.agda" type="external">erct-0010.agda</fr:link>
</fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A <fr:link href="foreign-erct-erct-004B.xml" title="Reflexive graph" addr="//erct/erct-004B" type="local">reflexive graph</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {A}]]></fr:tex> is called <fr:em><fr:strong>univalent</fr:strong></fr:em> when for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
]]></fr:tex> the type <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathchoice {\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}} x\approx _{\mathcal {A}} y]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link href="foreign-erct-erct-001I.xml" title="Proposition" addr="//erct/erct-001I" type="local">proposition</fr:link>, or (equivalently), is <fr:link href="foreign-erct-erct-001H.xml" title="Contractible type" addr="//erct/erct-001H" type="local">contractible</fr:link> with centre <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x,\mathsf {rx}_{\mathcal {A}}{x}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
]]></fr:tex>. We shall refer to a univalent <fr:link href="foreign-erct-erct-004B.xml" title="Reflexive graph" addr="//erct/erct-004B" type="local">reflexive graph</fr:link> as a <fr:em><fr:strong>path object</fr:strong></fr:em>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>We will write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {PathObj}]]></fr:tex> for the (large) type of path objects. In our notation, we will at times silently coerce a given path object to its underlying type of vertices.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
